wfStaDisable.name: wfStaDisable
wfStaDisable.description: Enables or disables statistical thresholds and alarms

wfStaPollInterval.name: wfStaPollInterval
wfStaPollInterval.description: The polling interval (in seconds) in which to examine objects in the threshold table for threshold exceptions.

wfStaThresholdEntry.name: wfStaThresholdEntry
wfStaThresholdEntry.description: Information about a particular threshold object

wfStaThresholdDelete.name: wfStaThresholdDelete
wfStaThresholdDelete.description: The row (object) deletion attribute for this threshold

wfStaThresholdDisable.name: wfStaThresholdDisable
wfStaThresholdDisable.description: The enable/disable attribute for this threshold. Setting this attribute to disabled, causes the threshold to be ignored in subsequent polling periods.

wfStaThresholdState.name: wfStaThresholdState
wfStaThresholdState.description: The state of this threshold. An invalid state means that the object could not be retrieved from the mib. A held state indicates that the maximum successive exceptions for this threshold has been reached and that alarms will not be generated until an exception occurrs at a new level or no exception occurs for the specified number of hold down intervals at which point it becomes valid again. An ignored state, indicates that this threshold is disabled and is not being polled. A valid state indicates that this threshold is under examination each polling period and no errors have been encountered evaluating this object for exceptions. A suspended state indicates that the object was not an integer type; user should manually delete the suspended object.

wfStaThresholdObject.name: wfStaThresholdObject
wfStaThresholdObject.description: The identifier of the mib object to examine for threshold exceptions.

wfStaThresholdLowValue.name: wfStaThresholdLowValue
wfStaThresholdLowValue.description: The mark for low threshold exceptions

wfStaThresholdLowEventLevel.name: wfStaThresholdLowEventLevel
wfStaThresholdLowEventLevel.description: The severity level of the event log message (alarm) to be generated on low exception

wfStaThresholdMediumValue.name: wfStaThresholdMediumValue
wfStaThresholdMediumValue.description: The mark for medium threshold exceptions

wfStaThresholdMediumEventLevel.name: wfStaThresholdMediumEventLevel
wfStaThresholdMediumEventLevel.description: The severity level of the event log message (alarm) to be generated on medium exception

wfStaThresholdHighValue.name: wfStaThresholdHighValue

wfStaThresholdHighEventLevel.name: wfStaThresholdHighEventLevel
wfStaThresholdHighEventLevel.description: The severity level of the event log message (alarm) to be generated on high exception

wfStaThresholdCurrentValue.name: wfStaThresholdCurrentValue
wfStaThresholdCurrentValue.description: The most recently computed threshold value for the polled object.

wfStaThresholdUnits.name: wfStaThresholdUnits
wfStaThresholdUnits.description: The units to be used in the determination of threshold exceptions. Absolute means that when the value object reaches one of the three thresholds, an exception is generated. PerSecond means that when the value/second reaches one of the three threshold values, an exception is generated.

wfStaThresholdAction.name: wfStaThresholdAction
wfStaThresholdAction.description: How the threshold should be evaluated with respect to the threshold marks

wfStaThresholdMaxSuccessiveAlarms.name: wfStaThresholdMaxSuccessiveAlarms
wfStaThresholdMaxSuccessiveAlarms.description: The maximum number of successive alarms that can be generated for this object before it enters a HELD state. A successive alarms is defined as two or more successive polling periods where an alarm is generated at the same level.

wfStaThresholdHoldDownIntervals.name: wfStaThresholdHoldDownIntervals
wfStaThresholdHoldDownIntervals.description: The number of exception free polling intervals which an object in a held state must pass before transitioning to a valid state.

wfStaThresholdLowExceptions.name: wfStaThresholdLowExceptions
wfStaThresholdLowExceptions.description: The number of low threshold exceptions.
